7. Challenges:

Limited Quantum Hardware
•	Current quantum computers have a small number of qubits. 
•	They are not powerful enough to handle large-scale aviation problems. 
•	This limits real-world implementation of quantum optimization. 
Noise and Errors
•	Quantum systems are highly sensitive to external disturbances. 
•	Errors such as decoherence and noise affect computation accuracy. 
•	This reduces the reliability of results. 
 
Scalability Issues
•	Most research is tested only on small problem instances. 
•	Scaling to real airline operations with thousands of flights is still difficult. 
•	Efficient large-scale implementation remains a challenge. 
Complexity of Problem Modeling
•	Converting real-world problems into QUBO models is complex. 
•	Requires: 
o	Mathematical formulation 
o	Constraint handling 
•	Incorrect modeling can lead to poor results. 
Dependence on Hybrid Approaches
•	Current systems rely on hybrid quantum-classical methods. 
•	Quantum part alone is not sufficient yet. 
•	This increases system complexity and computational cost. 
High Cost and Accessibility
•	Quantum hardware is expensive and not widely accessible. 
•	Most users rely on cloud-based quantum platforms. 
•	Limited access slows down research and development. 
Lack of Mature Software and Tools
•	Quantum computing is still an evolving field. 
•	Limited availability of: 
o	Stable frameworks 
o	Standard tools 
•	Makes implementation more challenging.
